2 Linear Regression

Description of the work for this week

The data is based on an International survey of Approaches to Learning. It was gathered in 2014-2015 in Finland by Kimmo Vehkalahti I have prepared a subdataset to for this analysis. It consists of 166 respondent and 7 variables. Background variables include age and gender of the students. Measures include Points (overall), Attitude (towards statistics) and three measures of learning styles: Deep, Strategic and Surface. see more

3 Linear regression

The dependent variable was Points. In the first model, the explanatory variables were Attitude, stra and deep. According to the results, only Attitude had significant relationship with the target variable. Thus, I made a new, simple linear regression model with only Attitude as an explanatory variable. The summaries of both models below.

Interpretation of the statistical test:

  • p-value for the model is less than .001 so the model is statistically significant.
  • p-value for Attitude is less than .001 so its relationship with the target variable is statistically significant.
model_1 <- lm(Points ~ Attitude + stra + deep, data = lr14)
summary(model_1)

4 Model interpretation

Multiple R-squared in simple linear regression is just the square of the correlation coefficient between the two variables, 0.19. This means that 19% of the variance in points is explained by Attitude. The Estimate for Attitude means that when Points increase with 1, Attitude increases approximately 0.35. There is a positive linear relationship, as can be seen also in the plot below.

qplot(Points, Attitude, data = lr14) + geom_smooth(method = "lm")

5 Model diagnostics

Is the model in line with the assumptions of linear regression? This is explored with the three plots below.

1 Are the residuals normally distributed? From the QQ-plot we can see that there is a reasonable fit with the normality assumption.

2 Do the errors have constant variance? In other words, the variance should not depend on the explanatory variable. Residuals vs Fitted -plot shows, that the variance does not increase when the fitted values increase.

3 Is there too high of an impact with certain observations? From Residuals vs.Leverage -plot we can see, that the highest leverage being less than .05 we dont have to worry that simple observations have too much power in the model.

# Model diagnostics
# Using par-fuction to place following 4 graphs to the same plot
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(model_2, which = c(1,2,5))

3 Logistic Regression

Logistic regression analysis with student alcohol consumption data.

This survey data is from secondary education of two Portuguese schools. It includes x variables about student achievement, alcoholc consumption etc. Data source and more information here: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Student+Performance

Explore the data

In this analysis, I will take four variables and look at their relationship to alcohol consumption. The exlanatory variable are: age, gender, address and absences. My hypotheses is that males, older students, student living is urban areas and student with more absences are more probaple to have high alcohol consumption.

Build Logistic regression

# build the model
m <- glm(data=alcs, high_use ~ sex + address + absences + age, family="binomial")
summary(m)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = high_use ~ sex + address + absences + age, family = "binomial", 
##     data = alcs)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -2.4240  -0.8261  -0.6250   1.0505   2.1305  
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept) -4.00961    1.76034  -2.278   0.0227 *  
## sexM         0.98222    0.24136   4.070 4.71e-05 ***
## addressU    -0.41405    0.28094  -1.474   0.1405    
## absences     0.09283    0.02325   3.992 6.56e-05 ***
## age          0.15088    0.10240   1.473   0.1406    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 465.68  on 381  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 424.90  on 377  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 434.9
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4

Interpretation: The estimate for the inercept is -4.00961, that is to log odds of being a high alcohol user and female, urban address, zero absences and youngest in the sample. From log odds we can calculate the odds by exponenting the estimate, that is -16. The other estimates tell us how much the log odds change if the explanatory variable changes. For example, if the absences (continous variable) increase by 1, the log odds increase .09283. As sex is a dichotomous variable, that coefficient 0.98222 is a log odds ratio between the female and the male group.

Z-value is a results of a statistical test which tells whether the variables power is statistically significant in the model (if z is >2 or <-2). p-value tells quite the same. We can see, that sex and absences are statistically significant predictors.

# build a new model with only significant predictors
m2 <- glm(data=alcs, high_use ~ sex + absences, family="binomial")

# calculate odd ratios by exponenting the coefficients of the model 
OR <- coef(m2) %>% exp
# and the same for confidence intervals
CI <- confint(m2) %>% exp
## Waiting for profiling to be done...
# print them out
cbind(OR, CI)
##                   OR     2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) 0.159445 0.1012577 0.2427684
## sexM        2.658116 1.6710354 4.2863129
## absences    1.101409 1.0549317 1.1548057

According to the odds ratio, males are 2.6 times more likely to be high users of alcohol. For every absence, the probability that the student is a heavy drinker is 1.1 times more likely.

.

Explore the predictive power

# Use prdeict() to compute probabilites based on the logit model. 
# type maked the probalities be probalities instead of log of odds, the default
probabilities <- predict(m2, type="response")
# add the probs in the data frame
alcs <- mutate (alcs, probs = probabilities)
# use the probs to make a prediction of high use
# threshold will be set to .5. If we want less false positives, we should increase the threshold
alcs <- mutate(alcs, prediction = probs > .5)
# crosstabs the target versus predictions
table(high_use = alcs$high_use, prediction = alcs$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   258   10
##    TRUE     88   26
# plot
ggplot(alcs, aes(x = probs, y = high_use, col = prediction)) + geom_point()

The confusion matrix shows, that there are quite a lot of false positives (n=31) and false negatives (n=73)

loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}
# call the function to compute the average of wrong predictions
loss_func(class = alcs$high_use, prob = alcs$prediction)
## [1] 0.2565445

The loss function calculates the average n. of wrong predictions, that is the training error. In this case the prediction is wrong in 27,2% cases. Its still better than flipping a coin.

# 10-fold cross-validation for the model
library(boot)
cv <- cv.glm(data = alcs, cost = loss_func, glmfit = m, K = 10)
# cv.glm computes the error and stores it in delta, print delta
cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.2591623

Accoring to 10-fold cross-validation, average number of wrong predictions is 0.25. Thus, my model is a bit better than the one in DataCamp (error .26). Wohoo!
